Workflow.comment:
# Workflow
A table for workflow pipeline scripts. It is using a URL to link to the script or notebook
of the workflow. A workflow can contain several steps, including: data extraction from catalog, 
data preprocessing machine learning model training or testing, and saving results and metadata back 
to the catalog. Deriva-ml package provides extensive methods for data curation and  ml running status management.


Columns:
- RID: An identifier of a workflow in the data catalog.
- Name: Name of the workflow
- Description: Description of the workflow.
- URL: A link to the actual workflow script or notebook.
- Checksum: Checksum of the file from URL.
- Version: Version of the script or notebook.
- Workflow_Type (Control Vocab): A controlled vocabulary to classify the workflow 
(i.e. Diagnosis Training, Image Cropping).

Associations:
- Execution: One workflow can be executed by multiple executions, one execution 
can only have one workflow.
- Workflow_Type (Control Vocab table): One workflow only belongs to one workflow type, 
one workflow type can have multiple workflows.

column_definitions.name: Status_Detail
column_definitions.comment: A detailed description of the current status.

Execution.comment:
# Execution
Execution is the instance of Workflow, instantiated by a user, on datasets, at a certain time.
It keeps track of the user, duration, status, metadata, input/output assets of an execution.

Columns:
- RID: An identifier of an Execution in the data catalog.
- Workflow (FK): The workflow run by the execution
- Description: A description for the execution
- Duration: The run time duration of the main machine learning process.
- Status: The status of current execution. The status can be: 
Pending, Running, Completed, Failed. 
- Status_Detail: A detailed description of the current status.

Associations:
- Workflow: One execution can only have one workflow, but one workflow can be 
executed by multiple executions.
- Execution_Assets: One execution can generate multiple assets like models, cropped bounding boxes.
One asset can relate to multiple executions, for example, a model asset can relate to the 
execution which build the model and the execution which use the model for prediction.
- Datasets: One execution can use multiple datasets, one dataset can be used in multiple executions.

Execution_Metadata.comment:
# Execution_Metadata
An asset table for saving metadata around an execution. Through Deriva_ml package, an execution
configuration file and runtime environment will be saved in this table. Other types
of metadata in any file format are also allowed to save in this table with association
to the execution table.

Columns:
- RID: An identifier of an execution Metadata in the data catalog.
- Metadata_Type (Control Vocab):  A controlled vocabulary to classify the execution metadata 
(i.e. config, runtime_env).
- Filename: Name of the actual file.
- URL: A hatrac url to the file.
- Size: Size of the file.
- ...

Associations:
- Execution: One execution metadata file can relate to one execution, one execution can have 
multiple metadata files.
- Execution_Metadata_Type (Control Vocab table): One metadata file belongs to one execution
metadata type, one execution metadata type can contain multiple metadata files.

Columns:
- RID: An identifier of an execution asset in the data catalog.
- Assets_Type (Control Vocab): A controlled vocabulary to classify the execution assets
  (i.e. Cropping_Model, Image_Annotation)
- Filename: Name of the actual file.
- URL: A hatrac url to the file.
- Size: Size of the file.
- ...

execution which build the model and the execution which use the model for prediction.
One execution can generate multiple assets like models, cropped bounding boxes.

asset type, one execution asset type can contain multiple asset files.
